{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"alias":"star-lure-chaos","description":"## Context\n\nThe plan-review gate's re-review of an *edited* plan does not converge: each remediation\nround can surface new issues in previously-clean criteria, expanding scope every run and\ncreating a non-terminating loop that drives cost, wall-clock, and agent non-compliance.\nThis is distinct from run-over-run reproducibility on fixed input (the LLM-as-judge\nself-consistency problem); the plan legitimately changed, so feedback *should* differ. The\nproblem we solve: a remediation re-review should validate that the surfaced issues were\nresolved **without** introducing different, lower-stakes issues that restart the loop.\n\nPrior conversation rejected three approaches: per-diff-region scoping (too blunt + new\nsection-diffing machinery), skip-clean-criteria reuse (unsound — reuses absence-of-finding,\nfreezes high-stakes defects an edit introduces), and whole-verdict probe (too blunt). This\nepic captures the chosen approach. Relates to the plan-review epic `5fd2-a7c2-0aec-48fa`.\n\n## What (the chosen design)\n\nA **rising-floor remediation re-review**: run the FULL criteria set every time (no skipped\ncriteria, no Pass-1 anchoring → full recall), and on a remediation re-review apply a\ndeterministic Pass-3 floor that drops only **novel, low-stakes** findings.\n\n- **Full Pass-1, unanchored.** Every applicable criterion runs; the finder never sees prior\n  findings (avoids the sycophancy/anchoring the research documents for conditioning a\n  generator on its own prior output). High-stakes defects introduced by an edit are still\n  found — nothing is frozen.\n- **Novelty as a narrow-question score (Pass-2).** Mirror how validity is produced: Pass-2\n  (which alone receives the prior findings) emits a structured **novelty** sub-answer set;\n  Pass-3 maps it deterministically to a novelty score, exactly as it maps the binary\n  sub-answers to validity. Chosen over `norm_id` lexical matching (too crude — false\n  novelty) and over freeform Sonnet matching (too unreliable). `norm_id` is retained as the\n  offline join key for convergence measurement, not the in-loop policy.\n- **Deterministic rising floor (Pass-3).** A finding is dropped iff it is novel (novelty\n  score ≥ T_novel) AND low-stakes (priority < floor). Carryover findings (matching a prior\n  finding) use the normal threshold — they must still be resolved. A high-impact +\n  high-validity novel finding is preserved (and can block). The convergence policy lives in\n  deterministic Pass-3, NOT in the LLM (the verifier scores novelty + severity factually,\n  never told the drop consequence — keeps it honest and preserves the \"no holistic LLM\n  severity in the decision path\" invariant).\n- **Freshness window = remediation-mode gate.** The narrowed (floored) behavior applies only\n  when the edit is part of an active remediation loop: plan changed, code unchanged since the\n  baseline, registry unchanged, prior sidecar (with finding text) available, and the last\n  FULL review within the window (default 60 min, configurable; measured from the last full\n  review so chained edits ride one baseline and the window forces re-anchoring). Otherwise a\n  normal full review (no floor). Code-changed / both-drifted → full review (the code-drift\n  path, `drift_refresh`, is untouched — out of scope).\n- **Floor height + window are configurable** and tuned from real data (already in hand).\n\n## Empirical grounding (already established)\n\n- Aggregating 245 `REVIEW_RESULT` sidecar events / 2,571 findings shows the verifier's\n  impact axis already discriminates (15% critical, 40% none, mean impact 0.43; attributes\n  spread sensibly) — so impact-discrimination is NOT a blocking prerequisite; the floor has\n  real spread to bite on and can be calibrated on this distribution.\n- The impact prompt nonetheless gives the severity attributes zero anchoring (vs rich\n  guidance for validity) → tightening it is a **robustness** item (consistency / outlier\n  control), not a blocker.\n\n## Already landed (observability foundation, this branch)\n\n- `scripts/plan_review_impact_distribution.py` — repeatable impact/severity distribution\n  report over the sidecar corpus.\n- `discriminates_impact_levels` deterministic eval scorer + `high_impact`/`low_impact`\n  dataset pairs on `plan-review-verifier.eval.yaml` — guards the severity axis the floor\n  relies on against future saturation regressions.\n\n## Scope\n\n- IN: full-run + deterministic rising floor for remediation re-reviews; novelty narrow-\n  question score; freshness-window remediation-mode gating; sidecar persistence of finding\n  text; impact-prompt tightening (robustness); config keys + docs.\n- OUT: the code-drift re-review path (`drift_refresh`) — unchanged; per-diff-region scoping;\n  skip-clean-criteria reuse.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- A remediation re-review (pure plan edit, code unchanged, within window) re-runs the full\n  criteria set, drops only novel low-stakes findings, surfaces/keeps carryover + novel\n  high-stakes findings, and converges to a signed PASS in bounded rounds.\n- The convergence policy is deterministic (Pass-3); the verifier is never told the drop\n  consequence. Pass-1 receives no prior findings.\n- Any precondition failing → byte-identical full review; code-drift behavior unchanged\n  (existing `drift_refresh` tests still pass).\n- Convergence-to-mediocre is an accepted, bounded tradeoff (carryover findings still enforced\n  at the normal bar; dropped novel findings recorded in the sidecar for observability).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Pass-2 emits a structured novelty sub-answer set; Pass-3 maps it to a deterministic\n      novelty score (mirrors validity).\n- [ ] Pass-3 drop rule: novel (novelty ≥ T_novel) AND low priority → dropped to overflow/\n      sidecar; carryover → normal threshold; novel high-impact+high-validity → preserved.\n- [ ] Pass-1 receives no prior findings; Pass-2 receives prior findings only to score novelty\n      (severity assessed independently of novelty).\n- [ ] Sidecar persists finding text (+ suggested_fix/checklist_item) so re-grounding has the\n      prior findings; a \"latest sidecar for ticket\" reader exists.\n- [ ] Freshness window gates remediation mode (config key, default-on; window default 60 min,\n      measured from last full review); code-unchanged precondition enforced; both-drifted →\n      full review.\n- [ ] Floor height + window are configurable; defaults calibrated against the measured\n      distribution.\n- [ ] Impact-prompt tightening landed as a robustness improvement (not gating).\n- [ ] Coverage on a narrowed verdict records narrowed=true + which criteria/findings were\n      floored; dropped novel findings go to the sidecar.\n- [ ] Offline tests (FakeRunner): convergence on a remediation edit; each precondition\n      fallback to full review; novel-high-stakes preserved; carryover still enforced.\n- [ ] Docs: `docs/plan-review-gate.md` section for the remediation re-review.\n\n## Out of scope / explicitly deferred\n\n- Decomposition into child stories (this epic is intentionally left undecomposed for now).\n- Any change to the code-drift `drift_refresh` path.","id":"7d43-49c5-bc4d-4926","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":["plan-review","convergence","re-review"],"ticket_type":"epic","title":"Convergent plan-edit re-review: full-run + deterministic rising floor"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1782753222615248001,"uuid":"d547848c-ac6f-438d-b898-57fa12017c8f"}